---
// src/pages/approach.astro
// The "augmentation without cognitive atrophy" thesis, three short sections.
// All prose below is placeholder — Miguel will rewrite in his own voice.
// The section structure (risk → principle → practice) is the bone we expect
// to keep. Edit the copy freely; keep the structure unless rethinking it
// deliberately.

import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Augmentation without Cognitive Atrophy — Solven Advisory"
  description="Augmentation without cognitive atrophy. How Solven helps PE firms deploy AI inside analyst workflows without losing analytical judgment."
>
  <article class="approach">
    <header class="approach-header">
      <h1>Augmentation without cognitive atrophy.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        The risk in enterprise AI is not adoption failure. It is what happens
        to analytical judgment when adoption succeeds.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="approach-section">
      <p class="designator">The risk</p>
      <h2>Cognitive offloading.</h2>
      <p>
        When an analyst can produce a polished draft in a single prompt, the
        formative work — sitting with the data, building a position from
        first principles, defending a number under pressure — quietly stops
        happening. The analyst becomes a passive editor of model output.
        Quality looks the same on the page; the underlying judgment thins
        out. This is the failure mode firms should be designing against.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="approach-section">
      <p class="designator">The principle</p>
      <h2>AI as adversary, not author.</h2>
      <p>
        We treat the model as a stress-tester of the analyst's reasoning,
        not a generator of it. The analyst forms a position first; the model
        challenges it. The analyst defends the work; the model probes for
        weakness. Used this way, AI sharpens the same skills that
        unconstrained use erodes.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="approach-section">
      <p class="designator">The practice</p>
      <h2>Workflow constraints that hold under pressure.</h2>
      <p>
        We design four kinds of constraint into
        <a href="/services#delivery">client workflows across diligence, portfolio operations, and investor relations</a>:
        analyst-first sequencing, where the analyst produces a defensible
        first pass before engaging the model; show-your-work appendices that
        make the human contribution legible to senior reviewers; AI-free
        training rotations that keep the underlying skills alive; and
        senior-led calibration reviews that surface drift before it
        compounds. The shape varies by firm. The principle does not.
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .approach {
    max-width: var(--container-prose);
    margin: 0 auto;
  }

  .approach-header {
    margin-bottom: var(--space-3xl);
  }

  .approach-header h1 {
    font-size: var(--text-2xl);
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    max-width: 18ch;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .approach-header .lead {
    max-width: 44ch;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .approach-section {
    margin-top: var(--space-3xl);
    padding-top: var(--space-xl);
    border-top: var(--rule-thin);
  }

  .approach-section .designator {
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-md);
  }

  .approach-section h2 {
    font-size: var(--text-xl);
    line-height: var(--leading-tight);
    max-width: 22ch;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-lg);
  }

  .approach-section p {
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    line-height: var(--leading-loose);
  }
</style>
